HEADWORD: Rile
<hw>Rile</hw> <pr>(r⟦imac⟧l)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Riled</conjf> <pr>(r⟦imac⟧ld)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Riling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See
<er>Roil</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To render turbid or muddy; to
stir up; to roil.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To stir up in feelings; to make angry; to
vex.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In both senses provincial in England and colloquial in
the United States.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rilievo</ent>⟦br⟧
